5000|$|Although <b>penny</b> <b>stock</b> {{trading in}} the United States is now {{primarily}} controlled through {{rules and regulations}} enforced by the SEC and FINRA, the genesis of this control is found in State securities law. The State of Georgia was {{the first state to}} codify a comprehensive <b>penny</b> <b>stock</b> securities law. [...] Secretary of State Max Cleland, whose office enforced State securities laws, was a principal proponent of the legislation. Representative Chesley V. Morton, the only stockbroker in the Georgia General Assembly at the time, was principal sponsor of the bill in the House of Representatives. Georgia's <b>penny</b> <b>stock</b> law was subsequently challenged in court. However, the law was eventually upheld in U.S. District Court, and the statute became the template for laws enacted in other states. Shortly thereafter, both FINRA and the SEC enacted comprehensive revisions of their <b>penny</b> <b>stock</b> regulations.|$|E
